@node "Restrictions"
@title "Guidelist v1.0 - Restrictions."
@{b}RESTRICTIONS:@{ub}

  There are a few restrictions while using Guidelist:

    * Spaces in file-, path- or devicenames are NOT allowed.
    * Try to avoid strange chars in file- and pathnames, etc. =*"#/

  Examples: (Files that will cause errors!)

    Disk 751:file.lha		( Rename to Disk_557:file.lha  etc. )
    Work:Dirty Pics/file	( Rename to Work:DirtyPics/file )
    SWAP:AW_C=64.LZX		( Rename to AW_C64.LZX - "=" not allowed! )
    
  Ok, I think you have got it! The reason why you can not use spaces is because
  of the AmigaGuide format. It will not accept them - so forget all about it...
  When processing files, downloaded with modem, this is no problem since spaces
  usually are not allowed on bullitinboard systems either.

@endnode

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Guides"
@Title "Guidelist v1.0 - The created guides."
@{b}THE GUIDES (FINAL!):@{ub}

After having processed some files, you will end up with some Amigaguide documents as stated in the @{"configfile" link "Configfile"}.
When viewed with Amigaguide or Multiview you will see filename, -size, -date and -description - Much like the ones used on BBS's, Aminet etc. (see @{"example.guide" link example.guide/main}).
When you click on a filename you are asked to insert the disk where the file is located - You will get a diskname. Therefore it would be wize to label your disks with numbers, and then rename the disk to this number...(!)
When the correct disk has been inserted a certain action will be performed on the file - depending on the filetype:

 - Archives will be extracted to a user-defined destination, see @{"Action Config" link GLAction}.
 - DMS will be written to floppy.
 - Pictures will be viewed.
 - Textfiles will be read.
 - Unknown files will be copied to a user-defined destination.

Known suffix are:
 - lha,lzh,lzx,zip,dms,txt,guide,readme,doc,dok,diz,man,nfo,asc
 - iff,gif,jpg,jpeg,ilbm,bmp,tiff,pcx,ham8,ham,anim,anim7,pic,brush,256

To perform this file-identification & action an external rexx-script called "ENV:GLaction" is used. This program got it's own configuration, which you may alter using a text-editor, see @{"Action Configuration" link GLAction}.
@endnode

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "GLAction"
@Title "Guidelist v1.0 - Action configuration"
@{b}ACTION CONFIGURATION:@{ub}

@{i}You need changing NOTHING in this file to make guidelist work - All paths & files are standart AmigaOS 3.0
@{ui}
In your final guide-database you are able to click on the filenames. When you do so a small rexx-script will be executed. This script finds out what type of file you have clicked and then it perform a certain action on this file.
Etc. if you click on a file called "photo.gif", the file will be identified as a GIF-picture and a user-defined viewer will be executed.
If you click on an archive such as LHa, LZx the file will be extracted to a user-defined destination.

To alter these settings, you must load the file "SYS:Prefs/Env-Archive/GLAction" into a text-editor. This can be done from CLI/SHELL:

  1:>Ed SYS:Prefs/Env-Archive/GLAction <RETURN>

In some of the top lines you will see the following:

  Dest      = "T:"				(Where to extract/copy files to)
  PicView   = "SYS:Utilities/Multiview"		(Viewer for pictures)
  TextView  = "SYS:Utilities/Multiview"		(Viewer for text-based files)

Alter the paths as you like, but avoid spacings!

@{b}MOVING GUIDES:@{ub}

If you want to copy a guide-database to a system where Guidelist have not been installed, you'll need to copy the file ENV:GLAction to the systems ENV:
@endnode
;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "History"
@Title "Guidelist v1.0 - History & Future"
@{b}HISTORY:@{ub}

15-06-96	v1.0	This release.


@{b}FUTURE:@{ub}

* The current version of Guidelist are not optimized. It is written in Rexx and uses RexxArpLib.Library to set up the GUI. Therefore it may occur a bit slow compared to assembler and C++ programs. Maybe I'll try to optimize the code and rewrite the GUI-part for some faster window updating.

* As you probably have noticed you can not use spacings and quotes in file- and pathnames. In many cases I could fix this, but it demands a lot of "IF..THEN.." coding which I'm not up to at the moment.

* The configuration file could be made much better.

* Error handling could be much improved.

Well, a lot of things could be done to make Guidelist better. But to tell you the truth I'm getting a bit tired of it...When I first started programming Guidelist it was for my own use. And the current version works fine for me!
You can contact me and get the commented source. If you like YOU can make the next update...?
@endnode
